Whekī is readily recognised by the black stipe bases on the trunk, the presence of aerial buds, the very harsh fronds,
and the characteristically orange-brown dead fronds. There are red-brown, rigid, multicellular, uniformly distributed hairs
on the abaxial surface of the costae. If the crown or upper part of the trunk is damaged, the aerial buds may grow out

In the field mamaku are readily distinguished by its tall trunk with black hexagonal stipe scars, and large arching fronds
with thick black stipes. The lamina and stipe scales have dark red setae along both margins, which distinguishes this
species from all other native species. Even very young plants of mamaku can be positively identified by this character.
Whekī-ponga is recognised by its thick fibrous trunk, skirt of persistent entire dead fronds, and crown of short-stalked
and rather narrow fronds. The pair of basal primary pinnae are less than 95 mm long. New fronds are produced in flushes
in spring, and are initially held upright, gradually drooping lower as they mature and die to form the skirt.
Cyathea smithii is readily recognised in the field by its persistent dead stipes and rachises with abraded pinnae, which
appear like a grass skirt around the trunk. The only other mainland New Zealand tree fern that regularly forms a skirt
are whekī-ponga, where entire dead fronds are retained.
